{
  "doc_id": "56176",
  "text": "Procollagen C-proteinase enhancer 1 (PCPE-1) is a secreted 55-kDa glycoprotein that can enhance the activity by which bone morphogenetic protein 1/tolloid-like proteinases (BTPs) cleave procollagen C-propeptides, thereby producing mature types I-III collagen monomers capable of forming fibrils [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Consistent with a role in collagen biosynthetic maturation, increased PCPE-1 expression is reported to accompany fibrosis onset in animal models of hepatic cirrhosis [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , cardiac fibrosis [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] ) and skeletal muscle fibrosis [CITATION_9] ) and in human dermal scarring [CITATION_10] . Differences in PCPE-1 expression levels in quiescent versus proliferating smooth muscle cells [CITATION_11] and the induced anchorage-independent growth of cultured fibroblasts in which the PCPE-1 gene has been disrupted [CITATION_12] ), have also suggested a possible role for PCPE-1 in cell proliferation control. It was also recently reported that PCPE-1 can bind the anti-angiogenic factor endostatin and can itself inhibit angiogenesis in an in vitro assay [CITATION_13] ). In addition, PCPE-1 may be necessary for lumen formation in a model of in vitro angiogenesis, although the latter effect may be secondary to PCPE-1's role in collagen biosynthesis and consequent effects on extracellular matrix (ECM) stiffness [CITATION_14] .",
